'''Diane B. Allen''' (born March 8, 1948 in [[Newark, New Jersey]]) is an American [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] [[politician]], who served in the [[New Jersey]] [[New Jersey Senate|State Senate]] from 1998 to 2018, representing the [[7th Legislative District (New Jersey)|7th Legislative District]]. She served as the Deputy Republican Conference Leader from 2002 to 2003 and as the Majority Whip from 1998 to 2001. She was the Deputy Minority Leader in the N.J. Senate. She was a member of the [[lower house]] of the [[New Jersey Legislature]], the [[New Jersey General Assembly]], from 1996 to 1998.<ref name=NJLEG>[http://www.njleg.state.nj.us/members/BIO.asp?Leg=156 Senator Allen's legislative web page], [[New Jersey Legislature]]. Retrieved February 23, 2008.</ref> Allen is the Chair of the National Foundation for Women Legislators.

==Biography==
Allen grew up in [[Moorestown Township, New Jersey]] and first ran for elective office in the 1970s when she ran for the Board of Education of the [[Moorestown Township Public Schools]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/insidejersey/index.ssf/2010/08/back_from_surgery_for_oral_can.html|title=Back from surgery for oral cancer, Diane Allen still has a lot to say|work=Inside Jersey|accessdate=March 1, 2011|quote=Allen grew up in Moorestown, a Burlington County town that was established as a Quaker enclave in the 1600s. Born to an engineer father and homemaker mother, Allen remembers stuffing envelopes as a kid for Republican candidates. Her foray into politics came in the early 1970s, when she ran for the Moorestown school board.}}</ref>

In the 1995 general election, Allen and Republican running mate [[Carmine DeSopo]] were elected, defeating Democratic incumbent [[Steven M. Petrillo]] and his running mate, newcomer Joseph P. Dugan.<ref name=1995Results>{{cite web |url=http://www.njelections.org/election-results/1995-general-election-results-general-assembly.pdf |title=General Returns for the Office of General Assembly for Election Held November 7, 1995 |publisher=[[Secretary of State of New Jersey]] |date=December 4, 1995 |accessdate=October 27, 2015}}</ref> The $1.1 million spent in the 1995 Assembly race made it the first in New Jersey to cross the $1 million spending mark, as reported in the results of a study conducted by the Center for the Analysis of Public Issues of [[Princeton, New Jersey]] that analyzed campaign finance reports from candidates for all 80 Assembly seats.<ref>Pristin, Terry. [https://www.nytimes.com/1996/03/13/nyregion/new-jersey-daily-briefing-1-million-campaign-costs.html "New Jersey Daily Briefing;$1 Million Campaign Costs"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', March 13, 1996. Retrieved June 22, 2010.</ref><ref>Staff. [http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PI&s_site=philly&p_multi=PI&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB32D08FA87AEF9&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM "Assembly Campaign Spending rises, especially in South Jersey. The Most Expensive Race Cost $1.5 million. A watchdog group says '93 Reforms didn't do the job."], ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'', March 14, 1996. Accessed June 22, 2010. "The District 7 race in Burlington and Camden Counties, eventually won by the Republican ticket of Diane Allen and Carmine DeSopo, was the most expensive in the state, totaling $1.5 million, according to Upmeyer's analysis of campaign finance reports."</ref>

Incumbent Democrat [[Jack Casey]] did not run for re-election in 1997, and in the Senate race that year Allen defeated the Democratic nominee Robert P. Broderick<ref>Petersen, Melody. [https://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/05/nyregion/1997-elections-legislature-after-intense-fight-republicans-fend-off-challenges.html "The 1997 Elections: The Legislature; After Intense Fight, Republicans Fend Off Challenges to Their Majority in State Senate"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', November 5, 1997. Retrieved June 20, 2010.</ref>

Allen was elected Chair of the [[National Foundation for Women Legislators]] in November 2013. The organization represents the near 1800 female state legislators in America, and supports elected women from all levels of governance.<ref>Staff. [http://www.burlingtoncountytimes.com/news/local/diane-allen-inducted-as-chair-of-the-national-foundation-for/collection_63d5e8e5-e09b-5985-8b15-ed542c314f49.html "Diane Allen inducted as Chair of the National Foundation for Women Legislators"], ''[[Burlington County Times]]'', March 17, 2014. Accessed December 4, 2016.</ref>

Senator Allen has served as a [[delegate]] to the [[Republican National Convention]] in [[1996 Republican National Convention|1996]], [[2000 Republican National Convention|2000]], as well as in 2004 and 2012. She has served on the Martin Luther King Commission since 1998 and the New Jersey Human Relations Council from 2003 to 2007. She has been the Senate's Deputy Minority Leader since 2006, and serves in the Senate on the Education Committee, the Health, Human Services and Senior Citizens Committee, as well as the Veterans and military affairs.<ref name=NJLEG/>

She was an unsuccessful candidate for the Republican nomination for the [[United States Senate]] in 2002. Six people ran, with Allen a close second to millionaire businessman [[Doug Forrester]] who won the party's nomination.<ref>Mercurio, John. [http://archives.cnn.com/2002/ALLPOLITICS/06/05/state.primaries/index.html "GOP, Democrats tout primary victories"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080115042809/http://archives.cnn.com/2002/ALLPOLITICS/06/05/state.primaries/index.html |date=2008-01-15 }}, ''[[CNN]]'', June 5, 2002. Accessed May 267, 2010. "In New Jersey, Doug Forrester, a wealthy businessman, spent $3.1 million of his own money to defeat fellow Republicans Diane Allen and [[John J. Matheussen|John Matheussen]] -- both state senators -- in the race to challenge Democratic Sen. Bob Torricelli, who faced charges of ethical violations during his first six-year term."</ref> Forrester won the primary with 44.6% of the vote, Allen came in second with 36.9%, ahead of third-place finisher [[John J. Matheussen]] who garnered 18.6% of the vote.<ref name=2002Results>{{cite web |url=http://www.njelections.org/election-results/2002pri-elect-senate-candidate-tally.pdf |title=Official List Candidates for US Senate For June 2002 Primary Election |publisher=Secretary of State of New Jersey |date=July 23, 2002 |accessdate=October 27, 2015}}</ref>

Allen was a television anchor and reporter for [[KYW-TV]] from 1976 to 1978, and again from 1982 to 1988<ref>{{cite web |url=http://geocities.com/tvnews1.geo/alumni_kyw.html |title=KYW-TV News Alumni |accessdate=2010-10-09 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091025183343/http://geocities.com/tvnews1.geo/alumni_kyw.html |archivedate=October 25, 2009 |df= }}, [[KYW-TV]]. Retrieved July 6, 2006.</ref> and at [[WCAU]]-TV from 1989 to 1994, both in [[Philadelphia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://geocities.com/tvnews1.geo/alumni_wcau.html |title=WCAU-TV News Alumni |accessdate=2012-07-09 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091025183339/http://geocities.com/tvnews1.geo/alumni_wcau.html |archivedate=October 25, 2009 |df= }}, [[WCAU]]. Retrieved July 6, 2006.</ref> She also worked at [[WLS-TV]] in [[Chicago]] from 1979 to 1982.

Allen received a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] from [[Bucknell University]] in Philosophy. She is the President of VidComm, Inc.<ref name=NJLEG/> She is currently a resident of [[Edgewater Park Township, New Jersey|Edgewater Park Township]].<ref>[http://www.votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=8171 Senator Diane B. Allen], [[Project Vote Smart]]. Retrieved September 15, 2007.</ref>

In 2007, Allen won re-election. She was unopposed in the Republican primary and defeated Democratic challenger Rich Dennison of Florence in the November general election.<ref>Reitmeyer, John. [http://www.phillyburbs.com/pb-dyn/news/112-04102007-1327938.html "Candidates for state Assembly, Senate and county offices file for June primary"] {{webarchive |url=https://www.webcitation.org/5QPFbmRaK?url=http://www.phillyburbs.com/pb-dyn/news/112-04102007-1327938.html |date=2007-07-17 }}, ''[[Burlington County Times]]'', April 10, 2007. Retrieved April 11, 2007.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.co.burlington.nj.us/election07/primary/primary060507.htm |title=June 5, 2007 Primary Election Results |accessdate=2007-06-20 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080425235328/http://www.co.burlington.nj.us/election07/primary/primary060507.htm |archivedate=April 25, 2008 |df= }}, [[Burlington County, New Jersey]]. Retrieved June 19, 2007.</ref><ref>[http://www.nj.com/elections/index.ssf/2007/11/7th_dist_three_republicans_see.html 7th Dist: Allen holds on to Senate seat], ''[[The Star Ledger]]'', November 6, 2007</ref>

Allen was considered a potential candidate for the [[New Jersey's 3rd congressional district]] seat being vacated by fellow Republican [[Jim Saxton]] in the [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2008|2008 election]].<ref>[http://www.nj.com/news/ledger/index.ssf?/base/news-0/1194673707176440.xml&coll=1 Saxton, citing his health, to retire after this term], ''[[The Star Ledger]]'', November, 2007</ref> However, she announced on November 29, 2007, that she would not run for the seat, citing factionalism in the [[Burlington County, New Jersey|Burlington County]] Republican Party in her statement.<ref>[http://www.phillyburbs.com/pb-dyn/news/112-11292007-1448567.html Allen says she won't run for Congress]{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''[[Burlington County Times]]'', November 29, 2007 {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>

On November 9, 2009, Allen announced that she has been diagnosed with an aggressive form of cancer.<ref>Hester, Sr., Tom. [http://www.newjerseynewsroom.com/state/state-senator-diane-allen-diagnosed-with-aggressive-cancer "State Senator Diane Allen diagnosed with aggressive cancer"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714174031/http://www.newjerseynewsroom.com/state/state-senator-diane-allen-diagnosed-with-aggressive-cancer |date=2011-07-14 }}, NewJerseyNewsroom.com, November 9, 2009. Accessed January 26, 2012.</ref> Allen had been informed in November 2009 that she had [[oral cancer]]. Though doctors had initially thought that treatment would require removal of her tongue and that she would be unable to speak normally, the surgery performed in 2010 did not greatly impair her speech, and she has since undergone radiation and laser treatments.<ref>Staff. [http://www.nj.com/insidejersey/index.ssf/2010/08/back_from_surgery_for_oral_can.html "Back from surgery for oral cancer, Diane Allen still has a lot to say"], ''[[The Star-Ledger]]'', August 17, 2010. Accessed January 26, 2012. "When state Sen. Diane Allen found out last November that she had late-stage oral cancer, doctors at the University of Pennsylvania Hospital told her they probably would have to remove a large portion of her tongue, leaving her unable to use her voice normally ever again."</ref>

The Broadcast Pioneers of Philadelphia inducted Allen into their Hall of Fame in 2005.<ref name=BroadcastPioneers>{{cite web |url=http://www.broadcastpioneers.com/dianeallen.html |title=The Broadcast Pioneers of Philadelphia - Diane Allen |year=2005 |publisher=Broadcast Pioneers of Philadelphia |accessdate=October 27, 2015}}</ref>

Allen, and her husband, Sam, are members of Mt. Laurel Friends Meeting and Moorestown Friends Meeting, where she currently serves on the Ministry Committee.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}

==District 7==
Each of the 40 districts in the New Jersey Legislature has one representative in the [[New Jersey Senate]] and two members in the [[New Jersey General Assembly]]. The other representatives from the 7th Legislative District for the 2016–2017 Legislative Session are:<ref>[http://www.njleg.state.nj.us/members/roster.asp Legislative Roster 2016-2017 Session], [[New Jersey Legislature]]. Accessed December 4, 2016.</ref>
*Assemblyman [[Herb Conaway]], and
*Assemblyman [[Troy Singleton]]

