{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}} {{Infobox military person | name = Mansour el-Essawy | image = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date|df=y|1937|09|18}} | death_date = | birth_place = [[Qena Governorate]], [[Egypt]] | death_place = | placeofburial = | placeofburial_label = | placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} --> | nickname = | birth_name = | allegiance = {{flagicon|Egypt}} | branch = [[Ministry of Interior (Egypt)|Interior Ministry]] | serviceyears = 1959-1996 | rank = [[File:Egyptian Police Major General Rank.png|center|30px]] [[Major General]] | servicenumber = | unit = [[Egyptian National Police]] | commands = | battles = | battles_label = | awards = | relations = | laterwork = | spouse = | children = }}
'''Mansour el-Essawi''' ({{lang-ar|منصور العيسوى}}, {{IPA-arz|mɑnˈsˤuːɾ elˈʕesæwi|IPA}}) is an Egyptian politician and the former [[Ministry of Interior (Egypt)|minister of interior]]. He was appointed by Prime Minister [[Essam Sharaf]] on 5 March 2011.<ref name=reu5mar>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/03/06/us-egypt-minister-interior-idUSTRE72508K20110306 Egypt appoints post-Mubarak interior minister], ''[[Reuters]]'' Africa, 5 March 2011</ref>
==Early life and education== El-Essawi was born in the [[Qena Governorate]] on 18 September 1937. After serving his two-year compulsory military service in an Army Engineering unit between 1955 and 1957, he was accepted into the Police Officer Training Academy. He received a law degree and a diploma in police science from the Egyptian Police College in 1959. He joined the National Police in 1959 as a commissioned officer. In 1973, he was promoted to the rank of [[Colonel]] was awarded a diploma by the Arabic Studies and Research Institute of the Arab League.
==Career== [[File:Mansour al Essawy Minister of Interior Egypt ARABIC.gif|thumb|Cartoon by [[Carlos Latuff]] about the Egyptian Revolution of 2011]]
On 1 July 1983, Essawy was appointed to [[Brigadier]] and posted as a Police Inspector-General at the general administration of inspection and censorship, and then became the undersecretary of the same administration on 2 February 1986. After being promoted to [[Major General]] rank in 1987, he was appointed Director General of Police of [[Giza]] on 25 October 1988. On 2 August 1991, he was appointed assistant minister of interior for Northern Upper Egypt Zone. On 2 August 1992, he was appointed assistant minister of interior for Central Upper Egypt Zone.
On 29 October 1995, he was appointed assistant minister of interior, Director General of police of Cairo, and was put in charge of the tasks of the first assistant minister of interior for Central Zone. He finally retired from uniformed service on superannuation in early January 1996, and on 16 January 1996, he was appointed governor of [[Minya Governorate]].
The state news agency [[Media of Egypt|MENA]] quoted Essawy as saying his priorities included reinforcing security across Egypt.<ref name=reu5mar/> Egyptian media reports said Essawy was previously the first deputy minister of security of Cairo and Giza governorates and an ex-governor of [[Minya Governorate]]. He was reported to be popular for his efforts to curb corruption.<ref name=reu5mar/> He was appointed interior minister to [[Sharaf Cabinet|the interim government]] led by [[Essam Sharaf]] on 5 March 2011, replacing [[Mahmoud Wagdi]].<ref name=alj6mar>{{cite news|title=Egypt PM appoints new key ministers|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2011/03/2011365436227288.html|accessdate=5 March 2013|newspaper=Al Jazeera|date=6 March 2011}}</ref> Essawi's tenure lasted until November 2011 when he resigned from office.<ref name=ana21nov>{{cite news|title=Interior minister Mansour El Essawy resigned, Military council approved|url=http://www.anaonline.net/news/default/view/id/3970/lang/en#.UTZMoTBSjm4|accessdate=5 March 2013|newspaper=Arab News Agency|date=21 November 2011}}</ref>
===Awards=== In 1988, Essawy was awarded the Order of Excellence first class.
